            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Solis is a product of Daly City, born to Filipino immigrants who arrived from Manila in the 1970s with dreams of stability for their children. His father, a nurse, and his mother, a bank teller, instilled in him a powerful work ethic, hoping he would pursue medicine. Mateo, however, was captivated by the distinct architecture of the Bay Area, spending his youth sketching the lines of Victorian homes and the imposing structures of San Francisco's skyline. Choosing to study architecture at Cal Poly San Luis Obispo was a quiet act of self-determination, a turn away from his parents' practical path toward his own creative one.\n\nHis career began with the requisite late nights and drafting revisions at a downtown firm. Mateo\u2019s meticulous nature and innovative eye for spatial harmony didn't go unnoticed. A key turning point was leading the design for a community arts center in Oakland, a project celebrated for its use of sustainable materials and integration with public space. This success solidified his reputation and propelled him to his current role as a Principal Architect, where he now manages large-scale commercial and civic projects, mentoring the next generation of designers.\n\nFor the last fifteen years, Mateo's anchor has been his partner, David, a landscape designer whose love for organic forms perfectly complements Mateo\u2019s structural vision. They bought and have been meticulously renovating a classic Edwardian home in Noe Valley, a project that serves as their shared creative canvas. Mateo's daily 5.5-mile commute on the MUNI J-Church line is a cherished ritual, a time for observation and reflection as the city unfolds outside his window. He sees San Francisco not just as a workplace, but as a complex, living organism he is privileged to help shape.\n\nAt 46, with professional success secured, Mateo\u2019s aspirations have turned inward and outward. He dreams of designing a landmark affordable housing project within the city\u2014a building that offers dignity and beauty to its residents. He envisions leaving a legacy not of corporate towers, but of thoughtful, human-centric spaces that give back to the community that fostered his own unlikely dream."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fourteen, showing his father a detailed sketch of a Steiner Street Victorian. His dad, smelling of the hospital, smiled. \"Beautiful, *anak*. A doctor needs a steady hand, too.\" The comment wasn't cruel, but it landed with the weight of expectation. In that quiet moment, Mateo felt the first real fissure between his parents' dream and his own. His passion wasn't a hobby; it was a calling he would have to answer for himself. This cemented his quiet resolve to follow the city's lines.\n\n2.\nHe was twenty, calling home from his dorm at Cal Poly after acing a brutal structural engineering exam. His mother\u2019s first question was about his chemistry prerequisites for med school. Taking a breath, he finally said it. \u201cMom, I\u2019m not going to be a doctor. I\u2019m an architect.\u201d The silence on the line was heavy with a disappointment he had feared his whole life. But on his end, there was only a profound calm. In that moment, he had finally laid his own foundation.\n\n3.\nThe grand opening of the Oakland arts center was over. He stayed behind as evening fell, watching from across the plaza. A group of teens had gathered, using a low, curved wall he\u2019d designed for seating as a spontaneous stage for a dance battle. Their joy, their unscripted use of the space, filled him with a profound humility. He hadn't just built a structure; he had created a possibility. It was the moment architecture stopped being about form and became entirely about life.\n\n4.\nFourteen years ago, standing in the gutted frame of their new Noe Valley home, he and David argued. Mateo wanted a clean, structural opening to the garden; David, something softer. Frustrated, David took a piece of charcoal and sketched nested arches on the raw plasterboard, merging Mateo\u2019s lines with a natural curve. In that moment, Mateo saw their future: not a compromise, but a beautiful synthesis of structure and life. It became the blueprint for everything they would build together.\n\n5.\nIt was a Tuesday morning on the J-Church just last year. Passing a monolithic 1960s apartment block, his eyes fixed on a single detail: a woman on a tiny concrete balcony, carefully watering a defiantly vibrant red geranium. The force of her will to create beauty in such a stark space struck him like a physical blow. His ambition shifted\u2014not to build another glass tower, but to design a home worthy of that geranium. And of her."
